Scott: I think it was mostly ads, obviously, because it was free, but I don't know what the hell was in that thing.

616
00:39:10,357 --> 00:39:11,140
Scott: I read it many times.

617
00:39:11,381 --> 00:39:13,813
Rym: I don't think my comic shop gave any of that stuff out.

618
00:39:13,853 --> 00:39:15,260
Rym: I just don't remember comic shop news.

619
00:39:15,361 --> 00:39:18,139
Scott: It was a very 90s thing, the comic shop news.

620
00:39:20,221 --> 00:39:22,765
Scott: So, yeah, the comics journal was something else.

621
00:39:22,825 --> 00:39:26,491
Scott: I didn't encounter the comics journal until much later, but it is quite old.

622
00:39:26,552 --> 00:39:28,635
Scott: I don't know if it exists anymore.

623
00:39:28,695 --> 00:39:31,420
Scott: It had times where it went digital only, I think.

624
00:39:31,920 --> 00:39:37,015
Scott: But this was made by Fanta Graphics, and this was like, you know, it was thick, right?

625
00:39:37,115 --> 00:39:41,240
Rym: And this was like indie- Well, because it was a bi-annual magazine.

626
00:39:42,081 --> 00:39:49,254
Scott: Yeah, and they'd be like deep, deep interviews with like indie comics people, like pages and pages long.

627
00:39:49,314 --> 00:39:52,660
Scott: That was like, you know, the real deal biz, the comics journal.

628
00:39:53,381 --> 00:39:58,033
Scott: And it went on for bi-annual, but it had like hundreds of issues, I think.

629
00:39:58,675 --> 00:40:00,960
Scott: It went on for a long- It's still going.

630
00:40:01,820 --> 00:40:02,341
Scott: It's still going?

631
00:40:02,381 --> 00:40:14,307
Scott: Okay, because I know it had troubles going in and out of print and digitally- Because this was a real deal thing.

632
00:40:14,368 --> 00:40:17,620
Scott: It wasn't some rah-rah, spend money, you know, rigid garbage.

633
00:40:17,640 --> 00:40:24,933
Rym: Rich Buckler sued them because they called him a plagiarist showing his art side by side with Jack Kirby art, and he sued them over it.

634
00:40:24,953 --> 00:40:27,318
Rym: I don't think he won that lawsuit.

635
00:40:29,660 --> 00:40:39,380
Scott: Yeah, so if you, you know, if you want to, you know, do some research on what was really going on, especially in the indie comic scene back in the day, comics journal, that was the real stuff.

636
00:40:39,540 --> 00:40:53,740
Rym: Yeah, and the thing I have to say about that kind, like in general, like these types of magazines is that they are really important for research, like modern research into the history of comics, the scenes at the time, because they're like- It's not quite an academic journal.

637
00:40:53,860 --> 00:40:54,800
Rym: But they're just, they're an artifact.

638
00:40:55,041 --> 00:40:56,419
Scott: But it's not a magazine either.

639
00:40:56,580 --> 00:41:07,300
Rym: They're an artifact with so much contemporary information about like a particular year in comics that like a researcher could have a field day cross-referencing this with other information.

640
00:41:08,382 --> 00:41:16,800
Scott: And it's like the amount of work that goes into making this thing versus what they charge for it is like just so dramatically, you know, imbalanced, right?

641
00:41:17,020 --> 00:41:26,059
Scott: I was surprised like, you know, how long it went on, like, wow, it's like it's someone's whole job to like work really hard to make this thing and they're probably getting almost no money for it, right?

642
00:41:27,421 --> 00:41:31,010
Scott: So the comics journal is definitely worth looking into, even back issues of it, right?

643
00:41:31,050 --> 00:41:31,792
Scott: Whatever you can get.

644
00:41:31,812 --> 00:41:34,620
Scott: I think there is archives of it you can pay for or get somewhere.

645
00:41:35,180 --> 00:41:36,460
Scott: Yeah, I guess it's not unavailable.

646
00:41:36,560 --> 00:41:41,859
Rym: I guess part of it is that I really didn't read a lot of superhero comics until actually like high school and later.

647
00:41:43,762 --> 00:41:48,860
Rym: I was so deep into anime that anime magazines are where I have the most like nostalgia and memories.

648
00:41:51,021 --> 00:42:00,400
Scott: So I guess actually, you know what, something I mentioned I didn't put on the list here that's worth at least mentioning a little bit is TV Guide, which obviously has no place in modern society.

649
00:42:00,621 --> 00:42:01,586
Scott: And is it dead?

650
00:42:01,606 --> 00:42:02,551
Scott: It should be dead.

651
00:42:02,671 --> 00:42:04,360
Scott: If it's not dead, it's close to it, right?

652
00:42:05,221 --> 00:42:13,300
Rym: I mean we stopped getting TV, like we even stopped, like we grew up in the late 1900s and TV Guide just stopped appearing in our house right when we moved.

653
00:42:13,660 --> 00:42:14,928
Scott: We never had to, we never bought it.

654
00:42:14,948 --> 00:42:16,860
Scott: We just used the newspaper's TV section.

655
00:42:17,000 --> 00:42:18,398
Rym: Oh, we subscribed to it and we used it.

656
00:42:19,240 --> 00:42:28,720
Scott: We did not, but it did have, parts of it were not just the guide part, parts of it were talking about shows and stuff and would occasionally talk about animated shows.

657
00:42:28,941 --> 00:42:34,240
Scott: So it is not an anime magazine, animation magazine, but parts of it were occasionally.

658
00:42:34,420 --> 00:42:40,040
Rym: TV Guide is how I would find out if an animated show I like would continue the next year or not.

659
00:42:40,340 --> 00:42:50,100
Rym: Like that was, or if it moved, like a show would move, like you kids don't understand what it was like in the 90s when you'd watch a TV show, like a cartoon, like Mask or something, even the 80s that you like.

660
00:42:50,420 --> 00:42:56,232
Rym: Cartoon, it's on TV, you watch it, every week you know it's on like Saturdays at 7 a.m.

661
00:42:56,252 --> 00:43:00,580
Rym: or whatever, and then one day you turn on the TV at that time and your show's not on.

662
00:43:01,080 --> 00:43:06,040
Rym: There was almost no way to figure out what happened if there's a different way to watch it except by reading something like TV Guide.

663
00:43:07,080 --> 00:43:15,300
Scott: Yeah, it's like, oh, is Sci-Fi Channel going to show in the late 90s, are they going to show some 80s cartoons at, you know, six in the morning on Sci-Fi Channel?

664
00:43:15,340 --> 00:43:17,740
Scott: There's no way for you to know that unless you have TV Guide.

665
00:43:17,941 --> 00:43:19,038
Rym: I remember, you know why we stopped?

666
00:43:19,140 --> 00:43:21,140
Scott: Unless you happen to flip to the channel at the right time.

667
00:43:21,220 --> 00:43:23,646
Rym: I remember exactly when we stopped getting TV Guide.

668
00:43:24,006 --> 00:43:29,960
Rym: Where we lived in Michigan, similar to how we got cable modems really early nationally, we got cable really early.

669
00:43:30,400 --> 00:43:33,900
Rym: And there was one of those early cable channels that would just scroll through.

670
00:43:34,200 --> 00:43:35,580
Scott: The cable channel tells you what's on you.

671
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:39,820
Rym: Yep, and once we had access to that channel, a TV Guide just stopped appearing in our houses.

672
00:43:40,700 --> 00:43:43,300
Scott: Yeah, so we never had, we never bought it, but I always see it at the grocery store.

673
00:43:43,380 --> 00:43:47,592
Scott: Anyway, so there was a Nickelodeon magazine, which is somewhat animation related.

674
00:43:47,632 --> 00:43:50,460
Scott: It was mostly just a kid's entertainment magazine from what I remember.

675
00:43:50,560 --> 00:43:53,039
Scott: I think my brother might have gotten it for a year or so.

676
00:43:53,540 --> 00:43:54,686
Scott: My brother got it too.

677
00:43:55,490 --> 00:43:57,640
Rym: I remember like half reading it.

678
00:43:58,080 --> 00:44:04,200
Scott: But I mean, it was animation related and it did, you know, I don't know how much it counts.

679
00:44:04,620 --> 00:44:07,700
Scott: But more importantly, there was Disney Adventures.

680
00:44:08,483 --> 00:44:13,120
Scott: So I never bought Disney Adventures, but I did see it on the checkout aisle at the grocery store.

681
00:44:13,582 --> 00:44:16,560
Scott: And it was sort of a digest size deal, like an Archie comics thing.

682
00:44:17,381 --> 00:44:24,180
Scott: And it was really interesting in that even though it was called Disney Adventures, I never actually bought it, but I would look at it occasionally.

683
00:44:24,681 --> 00:44:26,726
Scott: It had comics in the back, right?

684
00:44:27,027 --> 00:44:32,200
Scott: And those comics were often like tailspin comic, right?

685
00:44:32,240 --> 00:44:34,527
Scott: It's like there was good shit in there comics wise.

686
00:44:34,567 --> 00:44:47,520
Scott: And I'm wondering now that I haven't thought about this magazine in decades, if those comics, some of which were good, are like compiled anywhere that you can get because some of them are probably worth reading today.

687
00:44:47,961 --> 00:44:55,540
Scott: But in the front part, there was entertainment news targeted at kids and it wasn't exclusive to Disney.

688
00:44:55,841 --> 00:45:01,640
Scott: Even though it was Disney Adventures magazine, they would be telling you shit about like all kids media.

689
00:45:01,780 --> 00:45:04,487
Scott: Like other cartoons and things that were going on.

690
00:45:04,808 --> 00:45:22,000
Scott: So if you were a kid and you were into, you know, cartoons in the United States, and this magazine was still in print, which it is not, it was really like, you know, if I was born five years later, I probably would have had this magazine and learned all kinds of stuff about what was going on.

691
00:45:22,140 --> 00:45:24,680
Scott: Like new shows coming, going, movies coming out.

692
00:45:24,740 --> 00:45:29,780
Rym: Oh yeah, there's a whole list of all the original, like not based on an existing Disney property comics in there.

693
00:45:30,280 --> 00:45:35,680
Rym: Little Gloomy, Society of Horrors, The Last Laugh, Luna Park, Kid Blast Off, Gorilla Gorilla.

694
00:45:36,520 --> 00:45:43,140
Scott: This was basically, if you want to think about Disney Adventures magazine, it was like the print version of Disney Afternoon.

695
00:45:43,760 --> 00:45:46,226
Scott: It was like, it was pretty good actually.

696
00:45:47,589 --> 00:45:52,800
Scott: Even though I didn't buy it ever, I knew enough of it that I knew that it was the real deal.

697
00:45:52,941 --> 00:45:57,500
Scott: So you can probably easily get, you know, I don't know if people are scanning it.

698
00:45:57,780 --> 00:46:05,040
Rym: So it looks like they released, they released back in the day, seven volumes that collected all the comics that were in them, it looks like.

699
00:46:05,240 --> 00:46:06,140
Scott: Oh nice, okay.

700
00:46:06,240 --> 00:46:09,239
Rym: This might have been a long time ago, but I'll bet there's a way to get these comics.

701
00:46:09,380 --> 00:46:11,900
Scott: Which is probably hard to get also, but the library probably has them or something.

702
00:46:13,283 --> 00:46:13,464
Scott: Yeah.

703
00:46:13,504 --> 00:46:17,260
Rym: I'm going to bookmark this to remember to look into, to inquire about that a little bit.

704
00:46:18,160 --> 00:46:19,832
Scott: Yeah, I think it's largely forgotten.

705
00:46:19,852 --> 00:46:20,960
Scott: I haven't seen anyone mention it.

706
00:46:20,960 --> 00:46:24,399
Scott: I bet if I tweet like, hey, I remember Disney Adventures magazine, it might blow up.

707
00:46:26,281 --> 00:46:28,509
Scott: Anyway, so let's talk about the actual anime shit now, right?

708
00:46:28,589 --> 00:46:31,720
Scott: So I did not think about anime magazines at all.

709
00:46:32,821 --> 00:46:39,720
Rym: This is where Scott and I sort of switched places, because I turned into a weeb when I was in fourth grade, which was a long fucking time ago.

710
00:46:40,482 --> 00:46:44,260
Scott: I was, like I knew anime was a thing, you know, earlier.

711
00:46:44,622 --> 00:46:44,796
Scott: But when?

712
00:46:45,040 --> 00:46:47,519
Scott: I guess whenever, when Akira came out in the US.

713
00:46:48,100 --> 00:46:50,139
Rym: Yeah, I was a little bit, I was a bit before that.

714
00:46:50,641 --> 00:46:52,665
Scott: Was that 80 something, right?

715
00:46:53,527 --> 00:46:54,790
Scott: Late 80s, early 90s, who knows?

716
00:46:54,850 --> 00:46:59,420
Scott: I knew anime existed, you know, but I wasn't, didn't actually have access to anime.

717
00:46:59,500 --> 00:47:05,140
Scott: I would go to the comic shop and you see those Ranma VHSs there, but I didn't buy or watch those, even though I knew they were there, right?

718
00:47:05,460 --> 00:47:09,655
Scott: Dragon Ball was on, whatever, but I wasn't, you know, you know, Sailor Moon was on.

719
00:47:09,675 --> 00:47:11,220
Scott: I wasn't, I didn't actually watch that either.

720
00:47:11,901 --> 00:47:20,560
Scott: I watched Voltron and Macross, Robotech, whatever, but I, you know, I wasn't, I didn't actually watch Dragon Ball and Sailor Moon, even though they were on TV.

721
00:47:20,640 --> 00:47:26,580
Rym: But I went, like, by the time I was in middle school, I was already mailing strangers on the internet to get VHS tapes back.

722
00:47:26,881 --> 00:47:33,520
Rym: But it was a weird world, because again, late 1900s, I knew anime existed and I was obsessed with it and I would get as much as I could.

723
00:47:33,900 --> 00:47:34,400
Scott: I couldn't buy it.

724
00:47:34,440 --> 00:47:38,800
Scott: I would try to watch, anytime sci-fi channels showed anime, whatever, I would try to watch it.

725
00:47:39,020 --> 00:47:47,600
Rym: Literally watched every single anime that was in the local video stores, which was not that many, like maybe 20 tapes total.

726
00:47:48,003 --> 00:47:50,080
Rym: And I'd watch them all multiple times, like I was obsessed.

727
00:47:50,520 --> 00:48:01,940
Rym: But this was pre-internet, and even as the internet started to appear more and more, there was very little reliable or factually correct information about anime in America.

728
00:48:02,421 --> 00:48:05,019
Scott: Most of it would just be like a little GeoCities fan site.

729
00:48:05,260 --> 00:48:06,279
Rym: It was either, it was fan sites?

730
00:48:06,460 --> 00:48:07,878
Scott: You're lucky it'll be some JPEGs.

731
00:48:08,120 --> 00:48:17,400
Rym: But even worse, the fan sites would have content like, here's screenshots, or like, later on, here's an RM video of 10 seconds of the opening animation to like Ranma.

732
00:48:18,140 --> 00:48:21,599
Scott: But I'm a fan of the thing, here's the thing, I'm writing my thoughts about it.

733
00:48:21,780 --> 00:48:29,680
Rym: But also, nobody in America except people who were like, were professionals, knew shit about it, and kids would make stuff up about anime.

734
00:48:30,021 --> 00:48:32,560
Rym: So you couldn't even trust the information you could find.

735
00:48:33,300 --> 00:48:37,400
Scott: And there were zines, there were zines made by some smaller organizations.

736
00:48:37,501 --> 00:48:38,773
Rym: I was too young to find zines.

737
00:48:40,060 --> 00:48:41,680
Scott: And I had no access to those, though.

738
00:48:42,483 --> 00:48:48,700
Rym: I was going to gaming cons in the early 90s, but I didn't go to anime cons until 2002.

739
00:48:48,700 --> 00:48:51,520
Scott: I didn't even know an anime con was, you know, I didn't really understand.

740
00:48:51,900 --> 00:49:00,500
Rym: Yeah, Scott and I at RIT learned that anime cons existed when the people who ran the RIT Anime Club were like, hey, let's go to the anime convention.

741
00:49:00,621 --> 00:49:01,747
Rym: And we were like, what?

742
00:49:01,888 --> 00:49:03,114
Rym: There are anime conventions?

743
00:49:03,335 --> 00:49:04,080
Rym: Oh shit, oh fuck.

744
00:49:04,461 --> 00:49:12,358
Scott: Before I went to college, like, the idea of a con, it's like I sort of understood from, because there were cartoons that made fun of them, like that.

745
00:49:12,378 --> 00:49:13,320
Scott: there were Star Trek cons.

746
00:49:13,980 --> 00:49:17,140
Scott: And I understood that there was Magic tournaments, because I went to one.

747
00:49:17,320 --> 00:49:24,760
Scott: And I was going to a lot of- I understood that there were baseball card, you know, pro wrestling figure trade show type things, because I went to some.

748
00:49:25,402 --> 00:49:28,420
Scott: But I didn't fully understand that there were cons.

749
00:49:28,500 --> 00:49:34,320
Scott: And like when I was in the year 2000 in college, they're like something something Otakon, OhioCon, whatever.

750
00:49:34,521 --> 00:49:37,160
Scott: I didn't fully understand what the hell they were talking about.

751
00:49:37,702 --> 00:49:41,499
Scott: And I don't, I don't really, I don't remember how I ended up going to the one.

752
00:49:41,720 --> 00:49:52,840
Rym: Yeah, I would do a lot of gaming cons, which honestly not that different from what I do at PAX is today, except they're the old Grognard gaming cons where you'd have to schedule in advance and tickets.

753
00:49:52,900 --> 00:49:56,160
Rym: And they're very Gen Con-esque, just like shittier and smaller.

754
00:49:56,483 --> 00:49:58,019
Rym: Like I went to Michigan a bunch of times.

755
00:49:58,680 --> 00:50:04,039
Scott: But for somehow I like I understood they existed, but I had never conceived of like going to it.

756
00:50:04,660 --> 00:50:14,500
Rym: But because of this dearth of actual reliable information, it was very hard for me to engage with anime other than getting as much as I could and watching it.

757
00:50:14,861 --> 00:50:18,660
Rym: But I didn't have sources to know like who was involved, who directed something.

758
00:50:18,761 --> 00:50:20,680
Rym: Like it was just hard to find out those kinds of things.

759
00:50:20,680 --> 00:50:23,480
Scott: What other anime are available that I don't know about.

760
00:50:24,420 --> 00:50:30,700
Rym: Animerica was the first time I encountered any reliable source of information about anime in my entire life.

761
00:50:30,840 --> 00:50:32,754
Rym: And this started in like the early 90s.

762
00:50:34,500 --> 00:50:36,860
Scott: Yeah, so I didn't know Animerica existed until we were in college.

763
00:50:37,300 --> 00:50:41,480
Scott: I would skimmed it a few times here and there when it was lying about, but I never bought it.

764
00:50:41,822 --> 00:50:42,226
Scott: And why?

765
00:50:42,307 --> 00:50:42,974
Scott: I should have bought it.

766
00:50:43,014 --> 00:50:43,580
Scott: Why didn't I buy it?

767
00:50:43,660 --> 00:50:44,344
Scott: I couldn't afford it.

768
00:50:44,465 --> 00:50:47,440
Rym: I would read other people's copies, especially in high school.

769
00:50:47,560 --> 00:50:50,040
Rym: I knew people who subscribed to it and I would get their lead.

770
00:50:50,040 --> 00:50:51,068
Scott: Again, it made no sense.

771
00:50:51,088 --> 00:50:52,660
Scott: Like I should have subscribed to, you know, Wizard.

772
00:50:52,801 --> 00:50:55,800
Scott: I don't like, but I should have subscribed to that when I was a kid in middle school.

773
00:50:56,201 --> 00:50:58,700
Scott: And why didn't I subscribe to Animerica when I found out?

774
00:50:58,740 --> 00:50:58,961
Scott: Two reasons.

775
00:50:59,002 --> 00:50:59,605
Rym: One, kid brain.

776
00:50:59,625 --> 00:51:02,120
Rym: And two, like when I was young, our parents were very clear.

777
00:51:02,280 --> 00:51:03,820
Rym: Like we could each subscribe to a magazine.

778
00:51:04,180 --> 00:51:06,260
Rym: Like they're not going to let us subscribe to everything we want because we're kids.

779
00:51:06,940 --> 00:51:08,489
Scott: I subscribed to several magazines.

780
00:51:08,569 --> 00:51:09,715
Scott: I had GoPro, GamePro.

781
00:51:11,980 --> 00:51:13,688
Rym: Nintendo Power was the big one for us.

782
00:51:13,728 --> 00:51:16,219
Rym: That was like the magazine we cared the most about.

783
00:51:17,402 --> 00:51:17,666
Scott: Anyway.

784
00:51:17,727 --> 00:51:18,619
Rym: PC Gamer, etc.

785
00:51:19,322 --> 00:51:30,720
Rym: But Animerica was just the first glimpse I and a lot of anime fans in America ever had into like actual information about anime in Japan and the anime industry.

786
00:51:31,500 --> 00:51:34,000
Scott: So it was made by, so Viz made Animerica.

787
00:51:34,460 --> 00:51:37,578
Scott: But Viz was most of the anime industry at the time in the U.S.

788
00:51:37,638 --> 00:51:37,960
Scott: at least.

789
00:51:38,160 --> 00:51:39,999
Scott: So that they were covering most of the stuff.

790
00:51:41,162 --> 00:51:42,959
Scott: So it was a little bit Viz promote-y.

791
00:51:43,361 --> 00:51:46,859
Scott: And it did have manga in the back because they're promoting the mangas that they sell.

792
00:51:48,604 --> 00:51:51,160
Scott: But yeah, Animerica was kind of good actually.

793
00:51:52,060 --> 00:51:57,800
Rym: Especially because not only did nothing exist even like it that we had access to, but it was very informative, very well written.

794
00:51:58,340 --> 00:52:08,640
Rym: And it was also, while it was a little like it would focus on anime that Viz was involved with, it was also not as consumerist as the comic book stuff in America at the time.

795
00:52:08,860 --> 00:52:12,900
Scott: Yeah, they would show, they would put fan stuff in, you know, usual stuff, letters, columns, right?

796
00:52:13,923 --> 00:52:18,000
Rym: In retrospect, there were photos from conventions, but I guess I just assumed they were all like Star Trek conventions.

797
00:52:18,160 --> 00:52:18,637
Rym: Like I didn't know.

798
00:52:19,266 --> 00:52:20,120
Scott: Yeah, I didn't know.

799
00:52:20,483 --> 00:52:21,399
Scott: I blame a lot of that on Kid Brain.

800
00:52:22,500 --> 00:52:23,960
Scott: There's also Animerica Extra.

801
00:52:24,140 --> 00:52:26,300
Scott: Animerica Extra was just manga.

802
00:52:26,520 --> 00:52:32,139
Scott: And it was like a few chapters of a few different manga like compiled, but not as thick as like a real Shonen Jump was.

803
00:52:33,746 --> 00:52:34,459
Scott: So that was a thing.

804
00:52:34,820 --> 00:52:39,880
Scott: And what I find really interesting is I remember specifically like, was it 2004 or 5?

805
00:52:39,880 --> 00:52:41,580
Scott: It was like the anime boom.

806
00:52:42,240 --> 00:52:43,119
Scott: And anime was huge.

807
00:52:43,340 --> 00:52:48,639
Scott: You would think Animerica would keep going, but actually at the anime boom, like at the peak, they stopped it.

808
00:52:49,140 --> 00:52:58,260
Scott: And I think what happened, if I remember correctly, is everyone who had a subscription, they ran out your subscription with issues of Shoujo Beat instead.

809
00:52:58,641 --> 00:53:01,380
Rym: Oh, that's really common in the magazine industry.

810
00:53:01,481 --> 00:53:03,360
Rym: So remember the Disney thing we were talking about?

811
00:53:03,841 --> 00:53:07,200
Rym: They just ended it one day and everyone who was subscribed didn't get a refund.

812
00:53:07,361 --> 00:53:10,119
Rym: They just got Sports Illustrated for Kids until the subscription ran out.

813
00:53:10,920 --> 00:53:18,600
Scott: Yeah, it's like they stopped doing Animerica and Animerica Extra and they just did Shonen Jump and Shoujo Beat as manga compilation things only.

814
00:53:19,180 --> 00:53:21,320
Scott: And I think, yeah, you just got those instead.

815
00:53:21,620 --> 00:53:27,479
Scott: I remember at the convention, we were like at Otakon and they were like, "Subscribe to Shoujo Beat stuff going on," right?

816
00:53:28,384 --> 00:53:29,560
Scott: And that was the end of Animerica.

817
00:53:29,941 --> 00:53:32,940
Scott: So the other big anime magazine was New Type.

818
00:53:33,140 --> 00:53:35,260
Scott: So New Type I didn't know about until I got to college.

819
00:53:35,381 --> 00:53:37,280
Scott: And there were issues of New Type there.

820
00:53:37,361 --> 00:53:39,740
Scott: And there was a Japanese-only thing that someone imported.

821
00:53:40,322 --> 00:53:44,080
Scott: But it didn't matter that you couldn't read it too much because it was mostly pictures.

822
00:53:45,342 --> 00:53:53,018
Rym: Now, we talked about New Type USA and New Type on the show a few times because it was a moderately...

823
00:53:53,521 --> 00:53:57,200
Scott: New Type USA came out while it was a new thing when GeekNights existed.

824
00:53:57,480 --> 00:53:58,499
Rym: Yeah, in fact...

825
00:53:58,580 --> 00:54:01,260
Scott: There may be a New Type USA episode of GeekNights.

826
00:54:01,501 --> 00:54:11,980
Rym: So there is an episode from 2008 when we reviewed Bone and the news for that episode is that New Type USA is dead.

827
00:54:13,405 --> 00:54:13,638
Scott: Okay.

828
00:54:14,340 --> 00:54:31,460
Rym: So basically, the story is we saw New Type at RIT in the RIT Anime Club library and flipping through it, one, just images of anime we'd never seen or heard of that were like upcoming, that were not available in the US yet and a lot of text that we really wanted to read.

829
00:54:32,320 --> 00:54:33,620
Rym: When New Type USA was announced...

830
00:54:33,640 --> 00:54:34,320
Scott: Mostly pictures, though.

831
00:54:34,460 --> 00:54:34,550
Scott: Yep.

832
00:54:35,260 --> 00:54:41,419
Rym: When New Type USA was announced, everyone, like the Anime Club, us, everyone in America, anime fans were so excited about this.

833
00:54:41,900 --> 00:54:44,620
Rym: Finally, the Forbidden Magazine will get access to it.

834
00:54:44,620 --> 00:54:49,120
Scott: I mean, if you looked at a New Type in the early 2000s, if you just had one...

835
00:54:49,261 --> 00:54:51,480
Rym: It was like this big format, like glossy printing.

836
00:54:51,823 --> 00:54:53,960
Scott: For a Japanese person, it would be no big deal.

837
00:54:54,161 --> 00:55:06,960
Scott: But for someone outside of Japan who was a fan of anime and manga, seeing one of those things, it was like the print quality, the size of it, the colors on it, it was like an art book, basically.

838
00:55:07,240 --> 00:55:13,780
Scott: It was almost like getting a few pages of art book from every different anime art book and you could somehow get that monthly.

839
00:55:14,340 --> 00:55:16,214
Scott: It was just like this unbelievable thing.

840
00:55:17,120 --> 00:55:21,138
Scott: You wouldn't treat it like some piece of shit magazine like in An America and recycle it, right?

841
00:55:21,380 --> 00:55:22,010
Scott: It would be like,

842
00:55:22,030 --> 00:55:22,112
Scott: "Whoa.".

843
00:55:22,681 --> 00:55:23,480
Scott: So, fast forward.

844
00:55:23,660 --> 00:55:24,279
Scott: I got a New Type.

845
00:55:24,560 --> 00:55:25,639
Rym: New Type USA comes out.

846
00:55:26,282 --> 00:55:31,000
Rym: Like, we, however we knew, like pre-ordered subscriptions to it.

847
00:55:31,041 --> 00:55:31,700
Rym: And it wasn't cheap.

848
00:55:31,781 --> 00:55:32,840
Rym: It was real expensive.

849
00:55:33,743 --> 00:55:35,079
Rym: And we got the first issue.

850
00:55:35,841 --> 00:55:40,219
Rym: And what I remember is as I was flipping through it and looking at the pictures, I felt really good.

851
00:55:40,600 --> 00:55:43,860
Rym: But then I read the words and the words were nothing.

852
00:55:44,363 --> 00:55:46,160
Rym: There was nothing in that magazine.

853
00:55:47,625 --> 00:55:48,400
Rym: It was just pictures.

854
00:55:48,620 --> 00:55:50,200
Rym: It didn't say anything at all.

855
00:55:50,300 --> 00:55:51,400
Rym: It did not share any useful information.

856
00:55:51,400 --> 00:55:53,180
Scott: It was like, "Hey, this new anime is coming out here.

857
00:55:53,260 --> 00:55:55,997
Scott: Here's all the characters drawn from every different angle by the character

858
00:55:56,017 --> 00:55:56,400
Scott: designers.".

859
00:55:56,681 --> 00:56:02,119
Rym: The text under a caption for an image of a character would be like, "This is character so-and-so.

860
00:56:02,441 --> 00:56:04,378
Rym: She is very important in the

861
00:56:04,419 --> 00:56:04,580
Rym: show.".

862
00:56:05,183 --> 00:56:05,597
Rym: And that's it.

863
00:56:06,220 --> 00:56:07,359
Rym: The interviews were the most insipid.

864
00:56:07,460 --> 00:56:13,479
Scott: I mean, the magazine is really useful for artists, cosplayers especially, to get reference for things like that.

865
00:56:14,343 --> 00:56:19,720
Scott: And just to look at and see what... It serves the same purpose as like anime chart serves now, right?

866
00:56:19,780 --> 00:56:23,440
Scott: You could judge anime using a new type instead of animechart.net or whatever.

867
00:56:24,803 --> 00:56:28,780
Scott: But as a magazine, it left a lot to be desired text content-wise.

868
00:56:29,120 --> 00:56:43,340
Rym: Yeah, and it cratered pretty hard as everyone in America simultaneously realized that even if you don't read or speak any Japanese, you get the same information out of the Japanese version as you do out of the very expensive American version.

869
00:56:43,760 --> 00:56:45,780
Scott: Yeah, and it was very expensive either way, right?

870
00:56:45,800 --> 00:56:47,620
Scott: Cos it was so big and fancy and colorful.

871
00:56:47,780 --> 00:56:56,880
Scott: Now, the Japanese one did actually include manga in it and manga that were not available anywhere else, right?

872
00:56:57,042 --> 00:56:58,359
Scott: Or at least not anywhere else easily.

873
00:56:58,541 --> 00:57:00,740
Scott: So most famously, Five Star Stories, right?

874
00:57:00,800 --> 00:57:04,540
Scott: Which is a huge deal as it is a fascinating topic in its own right.

875
00:57:04,700 --> 00:57:07,920
Scott: But Five Star Stories is from New Type magazine originally.

876
00:57:08,720 --> 00:57:13,060
Scott: Full Metal Panic also originally from New Type magazine.

877
00:57:13,562 --> 00:57:18,440
Scott: And I think what's really funny is that New Type is named after New Types from Gundam.

878
00:57:19,120 --> 00:57:24,420
Scott: And I don't think there was any Gundam... I mean, there have been plenty of issues in there with Gundam stuff, right?

879
00:57:24,860 --> 00:57:31,580
Scott: But manga-wise, I don't think there was any Gundam manga published in New Type magazine.

880
00:57:33,908 --> 00:57:34,600
Scott: So that's interesting.

881
00:57:35,743 --> 00:57:38,400
Scott: But yeah, they didn't do that with New Type USA.

882
00:57:39,543 --> 00:57:42,279
Scott: There wasn't a manga in it that you couldn't get on its own.

883
00:57:42,986 --> 00:57:44,140
Scott: To sort of carry it, right?

884
00:57:44,561 --> 00:57:57,620
Scott: If New Type USA had included Five Star Stories in the same original order that the original New Type did, that's a really strong manga that if people read might have kept buying just to read that, right?

885
00:57:58,020 --> 00:57:59,780
Scott: So, anyway.

886
00:58:00,721 --> 00:58:01,714
Scott: As New Type was a big deal.

887
00:58:02,460 --> 00:58:12,700
Rym: I guess part of New Type's failure was that that insipid level of information was coupled with the fact that that was around the time when digital fan subs appeared for real and really grew.

888
00:58:13,181 --> 00:58:16,220
Rym: And also, legit ways to watch anime made it everywhere.

889
00:58:16,740 --> 00:58:21,180
Rym: And there were websites that actually had real information about anime that you could just look at.

890
00:58:21,540 --> 00:58:24,700
Scott: The New Type USA magazine specifically came too late.

891
00:58:24,860 --> 00:58:34,020
Scott: If somebody, maybe five to ten years earlier, had just simul-translated and published New Type Japan in English directly...

892
00:58:34,921 --> 00:58:37,620
Rym: Oh my god, if I could have gotten New Type in English...

893
00:58:37,944 --> 00:58:39,160
Scott: I think that would have been much more successful.

894
00:58:39,660 --> 00:58:41,340
Scott: Although it still would have been expensive.

895
00:58:41,961 --> 00:58:49,360
Rym: But I could have gotten New Type in English in elementary school when I was obsessed with anime, and that would have been the only thing I wanted for Christmas.

896
00:58:49,500 --> 00:58:56,540
Scott: If I would have seen New Type on the shelf at the bookstore in the 90s, yeah, I wasn't going to mess up and not buy that.

897
00:58:57,923 --> 00:58:59,540
Scott: Unless it was 40 bucks or something.

898
00:59:00,161 --> 00:59:04,380
Rym: And at that point, that insipid, useless information would have been more than I had access to at the time.

899
00:59:04,841 --> 00:59:05,062
Scott: Right.

900
00:59:05,503 --> 00:59:11,458
Scott: So, there was an anime magazine that also appeared very briefly around when I was in college.

901
00:59:11,498 --> 00:59:15,900
Scott: that I did buy, because it was issue number one came out when I was in college.

902
00:59:15,980 --> 00:59:18,956
Scott: And I was like, "Oh, a new anime magazine was called Anime Insider, I

903
00:59:18,996 --> 00:59:19,197
Scott: think.".

904
00:59:20,042 --> 00:59:26,740
Scott: And I bought the first issue, and I bought the second issue, and never bought it again, because it was basically Wizard Magazine, but for anime, but worse.

905
00:59:27,661 --> 00:59:32,114
Scott: It was so, like, nothing as far as content-wise.

906
00:59:32,175 --> 00:59:33,960
Scott: It was just ads and stuff.

907
00:59:34,823 --> 00:59:36,379
Scott: It should have been something to give you for free.

908
00:59:37,381 --> 00:59:45,139
Scott: But it existed, and I remember it, because I bought it off the newsstand two or three times when it was new, and then stopped buying it.

909
00:59:45,981 --> 00:59:48,732
Scott: But I just remember it clearly, because I was like, "Whoa!

910
00:59:48,832 --> 00:59:49,676
Scott: A new anime

911
00:59:49,716 --> 00:59:50,358
Scott: magazine!".

912
00:59:50,881 --> 00:59:55,400
Scott: And I guess I feel, personally, I like to start with a number one of something.

913
00:59:56,003 --> 00:59:58,720
Scott: So, something bad that just happens to be number one.

914
00:59:59,140 --> 01:00:02,620
Scott: Like, I'll choose that over an America number 100.

915
01:00:02,620 --> 01:00:03,216
Scott: For some reason, right?

916
01:00:04,862 --> 01:00:09,980
Scott: But what I think does... So, the last one, does it still exist today, Otaku USA?

917
01:00:11,887 --> 01:00:12,840
Rym: I don't know, actually.

918
01:00:13,701 --> 01:00:15,640
Scott: Does Otaku USA still exist?

919
01:00:16,301 --> 01:00:17,780
Scott: It looks like there's a website.

920
01:00:18,080 --> 01:00:22,240
Scott: Yeah, the sole surviving anime and manga magazine in the United States.

921
01:00:22,300 --> 01:00:24,839
Scott: And their website is things posted today.

922
01:00:25,242 --> 01:00:26,027
Rym: There you go.

923
01:00:26,148 --> 01:00:28,100
Rym: Nike releases some Gundam unicorn sneakers.

924
01:00:29,200 --> 01:00:29,320
Scott: Yep.

925
01:00:29,842 --> 01:00:36,640
Scott: So, yeah, I think this might still... If the website still exists, yeah, you can subscribe to it on their website.

926
01:00:37,143 --> 01:00:38,099
Scott: They'll sell it to you.

927
01:00:39,081 --> 01:00:43,060
Rym: The great and honorable Patrick Macias is still listed as the editor.

928
01:00:44,040 --> 01:00:44,110
Scott: Yep.

929
01:00:45,740 --> 01:00:45,934
Scott: Very cool.

930
01:00:46,101 --> 01:00:48,460
Scott: I mean, this... Yeah, this is still a thing.

931
01:00:49,101 --> 01:00:54,758
Scott: If you want, like, actual anime articles, content, editorial, right?

932
01:00:55,540 --> 01:00:56,939
Scott: It comes six times a year.

933
01:00:58,720 --> 01:01:00,530
Scott: You know, I don't know if it's just anime.

934
01:01:00,590 --> 01:01:02,440
Scott: I think it's all things Otaku.

935
01:01:03,642 --> 01:01:07,020
Scott: Even their website, you know, has headers for games, manga, cosplay.

936
01:01:07,140 --> 01:01:10,820
Rym: I think just between Otaku USA and Anime News Network, your cup overflowed.

937
01:01:12,002 --> 01:01:12,203
Scott: Right.

938
01:01:12,244 --> 01:01:14,859
Scott: So, but, you know, Otaku USA is still a thing.

939
01:01:16,060 --> 01:01:23,480
Scott: You know, you can get deep dives, real magazine-level, you know, articles about Otaku shit in English.

940
01:01:24,640 --> 01:01:30,820
Scott: I'd actually... Even though I know people who've written for it, worked on it, I've met Patrick Macias briefly one time.

941
01:01:32,701 --> 01:01:32,882
Scott: Right?

942
01:01:32,942 --> 01:01:34,889
Scott: I know it's existed for many, many years.

943
01:01:35,270 --> 01:01:37,518
Scott: I've never read a single issue of Otaku USA magazine.

944
01:01:37,538 --> 01:01:38,140
Scott: I'm not gonna lie.

945
01:01:38,262 --> 01:01:38,457
Scott: Yeah.

946
01:01:38,541 --> 01:01:39,439
Scott: I've never read it even once.

947
01:01:39,844 --> 01:01:40,999
Scott: I just know what it is.

948
01:01:41,040 --> 01:01:42,183
Scott: Was it for Otaku USA?

949
01:01:42,203 --> 01:01:48,299
Rym: So way, way, way back, I wrote a, like, it was just published.

950
01:01:48,760 --> 01:01:53,160
Rym: I wrote for one of these magazines a review of an early Otakon, like, as a podcaster.

951
01:01:54,021 --> 01:01:58,940
Rym: And I don't remember which of these magazines it was in, but it was, like, a four-paragraph review that I wrote.

952
01:01:59,001 --> 01:02:00,740
Rym: And they did, in fact, publish it with my byline.

953
01:02:01,221 --> 01:02:04,799
Rym: And then I didn't have time or energy or care to write any more articles after that.

954
01:02:05,741 --> 01:02:05,922
Scott: Yep.

955
01:02:06,626 --> 01:02:08,979
Scott: So, yeah, if you like that sort of thing, this exists.

956
01:02:09,802 --> 01:02:13,674
Scott: And the subscription cost for one year is 16... Oh, it saves $16 a year.

957
01:02:16,361 --> 01:02:19,100
Scott: So it's 20 bucks a year for the print edition.

958
01:02:19,620 --> 01:02:22,092
Scott: Print and digital combo, 25 bucks a year.

959
01:02:22,313 --> 01:02:23,519
Scott: That's not expensive at all.

960
01:02:24,382 --> 01:02:27,379
Scott: If you go for two years, they'll give you a free T-shirt, too.

961
01:02:28,040 --> 01:02:29,866
Scott: So... And that gets you six issues.

962
01:02:29,866 --> 01:02:34,480
Scott: 20 divided by six, that's, like, two or three dollars an issue.

963
01:02:34,780 --> 01:02:34,942
Scott: Right?

964
01:02:35,003 --> 01:02:36,178
Scott: That doesn't seem bad at all.

965
01:02:37,943 --> 01:02:38,966
Scott: If you like it, go get it.

966
01:02:39,006 --> 01:02:41,915
Scott: But, yeah, magazines as a whole are mostly dead.

967
01:02:41,955 --> 01:02:43,720
Scott: We'll talk about that next Thursday.

968
01:02:44,080 --> 01:02:44,149
Scott: Yep.

969
01:02:44,360 --> 01:02:46,180
Scott: 'Cause next Tuesday we're doing gaming magazines.

970
01:02:46,721 --> 01:02:46,842
Rym: Yep.

971
01:02:46,983 --> 01:02:49,260
Rym: And I guess next Thursday we're doing magazine magazines.

972
